hittington, Shropshire, England","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philippe, Alcee, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Rogero","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Cayetano, Jose, Silva.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Rogero</i> (see   Roger  ).","Catalan (<b>Rogeró</b>): from a pet form of the personal name   Roger  ."]},{"name":"Rieck","meanings":["South German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Ru(o)diger</i>, a compound of Old High German <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ (see   Roger  ).","North German: from a short form of a personal name containing the element <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Rjek</b>: nickname from Upper Sorbian <i>rjek</i> ‘hero’. Compare   Reck  ."]},{"name":"Rogelio","meanings":["Spanish; Portuguese (<b>Rogélio</b>): from the personal name <i>Rogelio</i>, Portuguese <i>Rogélio</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Roger  )."]},{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Roger  ."]},{"name":"Rogers","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Roger  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b> (see   Rorie  ).","History: Thomas Rogers (<i>c.</i> 1587–1621), born in London, England, was among the Pilgrim Fathers who sailed on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He died during the first winter at Plymouth Colony, but his son Joseph survived and married, and was later joined in MA by his brother John. This name was subsequently brought to North America independently by many different bearers."]},{"name":"Rogel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Jose, Jose Luis, Juan, Marcos, Margarita, Wilfredo, Adilia, Alejandro, Ana Gladys, Ana Maria, Anacleto.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Rogel</i>, an equivalent of French   Roger  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rogelj</b>: nickname or topographic name from <i>rogelj</i> ‘horn, point’, figuratively ‘tall young man’, as a topographic name probably denoting someone who lived e.g. on a horn-shaped spur of a hill. The surname in the form <i>Rogel</i> is found in Slovenia, too, where it is a less common variant."]},{"name":"Prosser","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Rhosier</i> ‘son of Roger’ (see   Roger   and   Rosser  )."]},{"name":"Rogerson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Roger   + <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Ritger","meanings":["Altered form of German and Dutch <b>Rutger</b> or <b>Rütger</b>, from the personal name <i>Rudiger</i> (see   Roger  )."]},{"name":"Rogge","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Bernd, Bernhard, Elke, Hans, Helmut, Wolfgang.","German and Dutch: from a short form of the personal name   Roger  .","North German and Dutch: metonymic occupational name for a grower of rye or a baker of rye bread, from Low German, Dutch <i>rogge</i> ‘rye’."]}]},{"name":"Powys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Powis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Powis","meanings":["Welsh (now mainly West Midlands of England): habitational name from the region of Powis in mid Wales (from Old Welsh <i>powes</i> ‘country dwellers’)."]}]},{"name":"Owain","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Perhaps derived in the Roman period from the Latin name <i>Eugenius</i> (  see  <b>Eugene</b>   ); alternatively, possibly from an Old Celtic name meaning ‘born of Esos’. Esos (or Aesos) was a Celtic god known to have been the subject of a cult in ancient Gaul."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","descripti